691
00:41:02,177 --> 00:41:05,930
- Hello. Sorry I'm late.
- You certainly are.

692
00:41:06,598 --> 00:41:09,016
- Jan, can I talk to you, please?
- Yeah.

693
00:41:09,267 --> 00:41:11,518
Just a couple minutes
in your office is fine.

694
00:41:12,395 --> 00:41:17,274
Griffin, you missed the formal
welcoming ceremony. You know Larry Levy.

695
00:41:17,901 --> 00:41:19,985
Of course. Hi, Larry.

696
00:41:21,655 --> 00:41:23,530
- Hi.
- Larry was able to get out of Fox...

697
00:41:23,782 --> 00:41:26,992
...earlier than he thought
and has come aboard as of this morning.

698
00:41:27,160 --> 00:41:30,329
Great. Well, let's, uh... Let's start.

699
00:41:30,830 --> 00:41:33,248
- Larry was in the middle of something.
- No. I wasn't.

700
00:41:33,416 --> 00:41:35,668
I was just killing time waiting for Griffin.

701
00:41:35,877 --> 00:41:38,837
Well, no. Finish. What were you saying?

702
00:41:39,047 --> 00:41:41,548
I was just saying that
I've yet to meet a writer...

703
00:41:41,758 --> 00:41:46,053
...who could change water into wine, and
we have a tendency to treat them like that.

704
00:41:46,388 --> 00:41:48,639
- As soon as you're finished.
- Not at this studio.

705
00:41:49,391 --> 00:41:52,142
Million, million and a half
for these scripts. It's...

706
00:41:52,310 --> 00:41:53,394
It's nuts.

707
00:41:53,895 --> 00:41:55,854
And I think avoidable.

708
00:41:56,773 --> 00:41:59,858
When was the last time you actually
bought a ticket to see a movie?

709
00:42:00,026 --> 00:42:02,903
- Actually paid your own money to see it?
- Last night.

710
00:42:03,905 --> 00:42:05,864
Pasadena. The Bicycle Thief.

711
00:42:06,032 --> 00:42:09,410
- You went to see The Bicycle Thief?
- I love that film. It's a great film.

712
00:42:09,577 --> 00:42:13,080
It's art movie. Doesn't count.
We're talking about "movie" movies.

713
00:42:13,248 --> 00:42:14,289
Jesus, people.

714
00:42:14,457 --> 00:42:17,459
All I'm saying is I think
a lot of time and money can be saved...

715
00:42:17,627 --> 00:42:19,878
...if we came up with these stories
on our own.

716
00:42:20,046 --> 00:42:21,755
Where are these stories coming from?

717
00:42:21,923 --> 00:42:24,383
Anywhere, anywhere.
It doesn't matter. Anywhere. Um...

718
00:42:24,592 --> 00:42:27,428
The newspaper. Pick a story. Any story.

719
00:42:29,055 --> 00:42:30,514
All right.

720
00:42:30,807 --> 00:42:33,934
"Immigrants Protest Budget Cuts
in Literacy Program."

721
00:42:34,102 --> 00:42:37,563
Human spirit overcoming adversity.
Horatio Alger in the barrio.

722
00:42:37,731 --> 00:42:40,441
Put Jimmy Smits in it
and you got a sexy Stand and Deliver.

723
00:42:40,608 --> 00:42:43,902
- Next. Come on.
- Larry, this isn't my field.

724
00:42:44,112 --> 00:42:47,156
Marty, it doesn't matter.
Just give it a shot. You can't lose here.

725
00:42:47,323 --> 00:42:49,283
Okay.

726
00:42:49,743 --> 00:42:53,787
How about, uh,
"Mudslide Kills 60 in Slums of Chili"?

727
00:42:54,039 --> 00:42:57,583
That's good. Triumph over tragedy.
Sounds like a John Boorman picture.

728
00:42:57,792 --> 00:43:00,669
You slap a happy ending on it,
the script will write itself.

729
00:43:00,920 --> 00:43:04,757
- Bon. Here, give me the paper.
- Gee, I don't know, Lar.

730
00:43:04,966 --> 00:43:06,550
Give it a shot.

731
00:43:08,386 --> 00:43:11,680
"Further Bond Losses
Push Dow Down 7. 15."

732
00:43:12,140 --> 00:43:14,725
- Okay.
- I see Connery as Bond.

733
00:43:14,893 --> 00:43:17,519
Funny. A good thing Oliver Stone
wasn't listening to you.

734
00:43:17,687 --> 00:43:20,147
- Where would we have been?
- We would have been spared...

735
00:43:20,315 --> 00:43:22,107
...having to sit through Wall Street.

736
00:43:22,275 --> 00:43:24,318
Marty, what did Wall Street do worldwide?

737
00:43:24,486 --> 00:43:27,029
Seventy, 75, maybe 80.

738
00:43:27,197 --> 00:43:30,449
Eighty million dollars,
a couple of Oscars. Nothing to sneeze at.

739
00:43:30,617 --> 00:43:33,827
Okay. I think Larry's point is well taken.
Let's move on now.

740
00:43:33,995 --> 00:43:37,748
Griffin, uh, can you give us an update
on the Taylor Hackford project?

741
00:43:38,166 --> 00:43:39,750
Griffin?

742
00:43:40,168 --> 00:43:41,627
Yeah.

743
00:43:42,879 --> 00:43:46,715
I was just thinking what an interesting
concept it is to eliminate the writer...

744
00:43:46,925 --> 00:43:50,260
...from the artistic process.

745
00:43:50,845 --> 00:43:55,224
If we can just get rid of these actors and
directors, maybe we got something here.

746
00:44:01,189 --> 00:44:02,648
Hello, Walter.

747
00:44:03,274 --> 00:44:06,026
- Make yourself at home.
- Mr. Mill.

748
00:44:06,194 --> 00:44:08,862
I understand you were kind of late
coming in this morning.

749
00:44:09,197 --> 00:44:12,533
- You all right?
- I'm fine.

750
00:44:12,742 --> 00:44:15,035
Appreciate your concern.

751
00:44:16,371 --> 00:44:18,664
What can I do for you, Walter?

752
00:44:18,873 --> 00:44:22,042
Don't tell me you came here
to pitch me a story.

753
00:44:22,210 --> 00:44:24,837
Ha, ha.
That's exactly what I've come to do.

754
00:44:25,004 --> 00:44:30,050
It's a good one too. It's about a writer.
Sort of. David Kahane.

755
00:44:32,554 --> 00:44:33,595
David Kahane.

756
00:44:33,805 --> 00:44:36,598
- Who's David Kahane?
- Oh, you met him.

757
00:44:37,183 --> 00:44:38,559
Well, I meet a lot of writers.

758
00:44:39,018 --> 00:44:41,979
Uh-huh. But this particular writer
that you met was murdered last night...

759
00:44:42,147 --> 00:44:45,816
...in back of the Rialto Theater in Pasadena.
- Murdered?

760
00:44:46,276 --> 00:44:49,903
Well, come to think of it,
Pasadena's as good a place to die as any.

761
00:44:51,698 --> 00:44:53,240
So, what's the story?

762
00:44:53,449 --> 00:44:55,409
Twenty-five words or less?

763
00:44:55,618 --> 00:44:58,745
Okay. Movie exec calls writer.

764
00:44:58,913 --> 00:45:02,624
Writer's girlfriend says he's at the movies.
Exec got to the movies, meets writer...

765
00:45:02,792 --> 00:45:07,212
...drinks with writer. Writer gets conked
and dies in 4 inches of dirty water.

766
00:45:07,422 --> 00:45:09,756
Movie exec is in deep shit.

767
00:45:10,925 --> 00:45:12,634
What do you think?

768
00:45:12,969 --> 00:45:15,929
That's more than 25 words
and it's bullshit.

769
00:45:17,307 --> 00:45:20,434
Pasadena Homicide doesn't think
it's bullshit. They got a complete report.

770
00:45:21,269 --> 00:45:24,521
You met Kahane at the Rialto.
You got drunk with him at a restaurant.

771
00:45:24,689 --> 00:45:27,941
He left before you did.
That's the last time anyone saw him alive...

772
00:45:28,109 --> 00:45:29,943
...except you maybe.

773
00:45:30,236 --> 00:45:32,321
Why are you denying this?

774
00:45:33,156 --> 00:45:36,533
Well, what do the police think?

775
00:45:36,784 --> 00:45:40,787
They think it's a botched robbery.
You know...

776
00:45:41,122 --> 00:45:42,623
...window of his car was busted.

777
00:45:42,832 --> 00:45:45,959
He surprised someone
trying to take the radio.

778
00:45:46,169 --> 00:45:48,503
There was a fight, he was killed.

779
00:45:48,671 --> 00:45:50,797
I didn't kill him, Walter...

780
00:45:51,674 --> 00:45:53,634
...but I went to see him.

781
00:45:54,510 --> 00:45:56,136
I know I said I didn't, but I did.

782
00:45:56,804 --> 00:45:59,890
- Why'd you lie to me?
- Well...

783
00:46:00,141 --> 00:46:02,351
...now's not a very good time for me.

784
00:46:02,560 --> 00:46:05,896
Haven't you heard the rumors?
I'm on my way out.

785
00:46:06,147 --> 00:46:08,982
Just what I need,
a little more controversy.

786
00:46:09,150 --> 00:46:10,776
Just not a good time, Walter.

787
00:46:12,153 --> 00:46:13,779
Look.

788
00:46:14,530 --> 00:46:17,991
I am in charge of studio security
in every definition of the word...

789
00:46:18,159 --> 00:46:21,536
...which means it is my job
to take care of a studio executive...

790
00:46:21,788 --> 00:46:25,457
...should he be, uh, shall we say,
under suspicion of murder...

791
00:46:25,625 --> 00:46:29,503
...at a time when profits are down and
the company is vulnerable for a takeover.

792
00:46:29,712 --> 00:46:32,798
It is my job to keep this
very, very, very, very quiet!

793
00:46:34,175 --> 00:46:35,884
You wanna help?

794
00:46:36,386 --> 00:46:39,179
- Of course.
- Then stop lying.

795
00:46:40,014 --> 00:46:42,849
- How many meetings did you have?
- One.

796
00:46:43,059 --> 00:46:45,686
- Not counting last night?
- Not counting last night.

797
00:46:45,853 --> 00:46:48,021
Why'd you go all the way
to Pasadena to meet?

798
00:46:48,189 --> 00:46:51,024
He had an idea I was interested in.
I wanted to talk to him.

799
00:46:51,192 --> 00:46:52,359
His girlfriend.

800
00:46:52,568 --> 00:46:55,696
I guess she was a friend of yours too.
Think fast!

801
00:46:55,863 --> 00:46:58,532
Jesus Christ, Walter,
what do you think? What is this?

802
00:46:58,741 --> 00:47:01,827
The third degree. If you don't like it,
wait till the police start asking.

803
00:47:01,995 --> 00:47:03,954
- I'll go right now.
- They'll be a lot less polite!

804
00:47:04,122 --> 00:47:07,749
- You come with me!
- You're acting like someone's who's guilty.

805
00:47:08,084 --> 00:47:09,710
You're not guilty, are you?

806
00:47:10,044 --> 00:47:12,045
For the last time, I'm not a murderer.

807
00:47:29,397 --> 00:47:31,148
Bad news?

808
00:47:31,899 --> 00:47:35,485
- What?
- The fax. Is it bad news?

809
00:47:35,737 --> 00:47:36,862
No.

810
00:47:38,448 --> 00:47:39,865
Business as usual.

811
00:47:41,451 --> 00:47:44,953
The Hollywood system
did not murder David Kahane.

812
00:47:45,371 --> 00:47:48,415
Not the $98-million movie,
not the $12-million actor.

813
00:47:48,583 --> 00:47:54,087
Not even the million-dollar deal
that David Kahane never landed.

814
00:47:54,255 --> 00:48:00,510
No, the most that we can pin on Hollywood
is assault with intent to kill.

815
00:48:01,012 --> 00:48:05,891
Because society is responsible
for this particular murder...

816
00:48:06,100 --> 00:48:11,688
...and it is to society that we must look
if we are to have any justice for that crime.

817
00:48:11,856 --> 00:48:14,149
Because someone in the night...

818
00:48:14,692 --> 00:48:19,613
...killed David Kahane, and that person
will have to bear the guilt.

819
00:48:20,823 --> 00:48:26,703
And if David were here right now,
I know in my heart that he would say:

820
00:48:27,413 --> 00:48:29,956
"Cut the shit, Phil.

821
00:48:30,208 --> 00:48:34,169
What did you learn from all of this?
Did you learn anything from this?"

822
00:48:34,420 --> 00:48:37,381
And I'd say,
"Uh, yeah, David, uh, I've learned a lot.

823
00:48:37,548 --> 00:48:40,467
We here, uh... We'll take it from here."

824
00:48:40,843 --> 00:48:44,638
And the next time we sell a script
for a million dollars...

825
00:48:44,931 --> 00:48:48,308
...the next time we nail some
shit-bag producer to the wall, we'll say:

826
00:48:48,476 --> 00:48:50,811
"That's another one for David Kahane."

827
00:48:54,440 --> 00:48:58,735
David was working on something the day
he died. I'd, uh, like to share it with you.

828
00:48:59,654 --> 00:49:02,656
"Blackness. A mangy dog barks.

829
00:49:03,449 --> 00:49:08,453
Garbage can lids are lifted
as derelicts in the street hunt for food.

830
00:49:08,663 --> 00:49:11,081
Buzzing, as a cheap alarm clock
goes off.

831
00:49:11,457 --> 00:49:14,584
Interior. Flophouse room. Early morning.

832
00:49:14,836 --> 00:49:17,838
A tracking shot moves
through the grimy room.

833
00:49:18,047 --> 00:49:21,550
Light streams in through holes
in the yellowing window shades.

834
00:49:21,759 --> 00:49:24,344
Moths dance in the beams of light.

835
00:49:24,554 --> 00:49:27,681
Track down along the floor.
The frayed rug.

836
00:49:27,849 --> 00:49:30,725
Stop on an old shoe.

837
00:49:30,977 --> 00:49:32,602
It's empty."

838
00:49:37,233 --> 00:49:39,025
That's as far as he got.

839
00:49:40,236 --> 00:49:42,529
That's the last thing he wrote.

840
00:49:43,614 --> 00:49:45,407
So long, Dave.

841
00:49:46,075 --> 00:49:47,742
Fade out.

842
00:49:48,453 --> 00:49:49,703
Thank you.

843
00:50:05,928 --> 00:50:09,222
Who are you? You're not a writer.

844
00:50:10,141 --> 00:50:12,392
No. I'm Griffin Mill.

845
00:50:12,602 --> 00:50:17,230
- We spoke the night David was...
- Blue sea, white sea. Yes.

846
00:50:17,440 --> 00:50:18,982
It turned out you were right.

847
00:50:19,150 --> 00:50:21,943
- What?
- It was a red sea.

848
00:50:22,528 --> 00:50:24,905
Oh. Yeah.

849
00:50:26,532 --> 00:50:29,159
You're the only person I know here.

850
00:50:29,744 --> 00:50:32,454
Listen, I'm really sorry about David.

851
00:50:32,747 --> 00:50:34,539
He was, uh...

852
00:50:34,957 --> 00:50:36,708
...a talent.

853
00:50:37,043 --> 00:50:39,085
You really think so?

854
00:50:39,420 --> 00:50:42,130
I always suspected he was...

855
00:50:42,590 --> 00:50:45,842
...uniquely untalented.

856
00:50:46,719 --> 00:50:48,094
It's nice of you to say that.

857
00:50:48,262 --> 00:50:51,556
- Nice of you to come. You didn't have to.
- Well, I did.

858
00:50:51,933 --> 00:50:55,602
You know, I was probably
the last person to see him alive.

859
00:50:55,770 --> 00:50:58,146
Yeah. The police told me.

860
00:50:58,606 --> 00:51:02,192
- Well, not quite the last, surely.
- No.

861
00:51:03,819 --> 00:51:06,780
I'm sure this is a terrible time for you.

862
00:51:07,114 --> 00:51:09,157
Is there anything you need or?

863
00:51:09,367 --> 00:51:11,576
No, really. I...

864
00:51:11,744 --> 00:51:13,995
I don't feel bad.

865
00:51:14,205 --> 00:51:16,957
It's like when my parents died.

866
00:51:17,124 --> 00:51:21,378
I didn't feel anything at all.
They were just gone.

867
00:51:22,380 --> 00:51:25,507
Well, I'm sure it hasn't sunk in yet.

868
00:51:25,716 --> 00:51:28,969
- That was years ago.
- No, I meant David.

869
00:51:29,136 --> 00:51:30,387
Oh.

870
00:51:30,555 --> 00:51:32,013
Oh, God.

871
00:51:32,223 --> 00:51:35,225
These people. I don't like it here.

872
00:51:35,476 --> 00:51:41,648
They're all expecting me to grieve
and mourn, and I can't talk to them.

873
00:51:43,150 --> 00:51:45,318
David's gone...

874
00:51:45,653 --> 00:51:47,988
...and I'm somewhere else already.

875
00:51:48,322 --> 00:51:51,116
- Will you take me home?
- What?

876
00:51:51,284 --> 00:51:53,243
Will you take me home?

877
00:51:54,036 --> 00:51:57,038
Sure. I'm right here.

878
00:52:33,909 --> 00:52:36,202
These are very interesting. I like them.

879
00:52:36,370 --> 00:52:40,040
- Would you like a drink?
- No, thanks.

880
00:52:40,374 --> 00:52:42,417
- Where do you show?
- Hmm?

881
00:52:42,585 --> 00:52:43,710
Gallery. What gallery?

882
00:52:43,878 --> 00:52:46,546
- Who's your dealer?
- I don't have a dealer.

883
00:52:46,756 --> 00:52:49,090
I couldn't sell these.
They're never finished.

884
00:52:49,258 --> 00:52:50,884
Bicky?

885
00:52:51,469 --> 00:52:54,179
No, thanks. They're never finished?

886
00:52:54,388 --> 00:52:58,683
No, they're just what I do, for myself.

887
00:52:58,893 --> 00:53:00,727
What I feel.

888
00:53:01,937 --> 00:53:04,230
You ask lots of questions, Mr. Mill.

889
00:53:04,732 --> 00:53:08,735
You're just like the police.
That's all they did, ask questions.

890
00:53:09,904 --> 00:53:11,571
They asked me a lot about you.

891
00:53:11,739 --> 00:53:13,531
- Did they?
- Mm-hm.

892
00:53:13,699 --> 00:53:17,369
How long we've known each other,
if you'd ever been to the house before.

893
00:53:17,536 --> 00:53:20,455
Well, I suppose they have to ask
those questions.

894
00:53:20,748 --> 00:53:22,415
I don't see why.

895
00:53:22,750 --> 00:53:25,085
Because that's what police do.

896
00:53:25,795 --> 00:53:28,505
- Can I ask you a question?
- Sure.

897
00:53:29,090 --> 00:53:31,466
Why was it so important
to see David that night?

898
00:53:31,717 --> 00:53:33,593
What was so urgent?

899
00:53:35,721 --> 00:53:38,348
Well, he pitched me a story
a few months ago and...

900
00:53:38,599 --> 00:53:40,725
- The Japan story, right?
- Yes, the Japan story.

901
00:53:40,935 --> 00:53:44,604
I liked it at the time, but it needed work,
especially the ending.

902
00:53:44,772 --> 00:53:47,273
And I was sitting in my office that day...

903
00:53:47,441 --> 00:53:50,318
...and it suddenly occurred to me
how to make the ending work.

904
00:53:50,528 --> 00:53:52,612
So, what was it?

905
00:53:52,947 --> 00:53:56,449
- What?
- Your idea for the ending?

906
00:53:57,284 --> 00:53:58,785
Up.

907
00:53:59,495 --> 00:54:00,995
- "Up"?
- Up.

908
00:54:01,247 --> 00:54:04,165
- What does that mean?
- As opposed to down. Moods.

909
00:54:04,458 --> 00:54:07,627
You know, happy as opposed to sad,
hopeful as opposed to depressing.

910
00:54:08,546 --> 00:54:11,464
- What did you think of his ending?
- I never read it.

911
00:54:13,300 --> 00:54:15,969
- You never read it?
- Nope.

912
00:54:16,178 --> 00:54:18,179
I don't like reading.

913
00:54:18,472 --> 00:54:21,558
- Do you like books?
- I like words...

914
00:54:21,809 --> 00:54:23,476
...and letters...

915
00:54:23,686 --> 00:54:26,062
...but I'm not crazy
about complete sentences.

916
00:54:26,689 --> 00:54:27,814
Hmm.

917
00:54:27,982 --> 00:54:29,691
So, what did he think?

918
00:54:30,651 --> 00:54:34,195
He walked out on me, actually.
I don't think David liked me very much.

919
00:54:34,697 --> 00:54:38,908
I think he just didn't like happy endings.

920
00:54:42,204 --> 00:54:44,164
Put your face here.

921
00:54:45,541 --> 00:54:47,333
Great.

922
00:54:49,170 --> 00:54:51,713
What are you doing?
You're not gonna paint me, are you?

923
00:54:51,881 --> 00:54:55,049
I might put you in one of my paintings.

924
00:54:55,342 --> 00:54:58,678
There's one that I want to do
of an Icelandic hero.

925
00:54:58,888 --> 00:55:01,931
He's a thief and he's made of fire.

926
00:55:02,183 --> 00:55:04,517
- Hmm, but you might not like that.
